    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Segregation at the Bookstore</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Anthony Q Fletcher letter deplores Ward Connerly's 'tirade' about something so inconsequential as literary 'redlining'; holds Connerly should be more concerned about issues like African-American illiteracy rates</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Ward Connerly (''Where 'Separate but Equal' Still Rules,'' Op-Ed, May 8) has once again shocked my sensibilities with his tirade about something as inconsequential as literary ''redlining.'' Wasting time on the segregation of books and authors in bookstores with greater public policy challenges before us is senseless.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Ward Connerly (''Where 'Separate but Equal' Still Rules,'' Op-Ed, May 8) has once again shocked my sensibilities with his tirade about something as inconsequential as literary ''redlining.'' Wasting time on the segregation of books and authors in bookstores with greater public policy challenges before us is senseless.</p>
        <p>Perhaps Mr. Connerly should be more concerned with African-American illiteracy rates and whether or not we can even read these books.</p>
        <p>ANTHONY Q. FLETCHER  Stamford, Conn., May 8, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is an adjunct assistant professor of black studies at City College, CUNY.</p>
      </block>
